# Chapter 6 — Finite Wells, Steps, and Barriers
*Why walls that end are more interesting than walls that don't.*

In 1928 Friedrich Hund sat down with a nitrogen molecule and found the new wave mechanics whispering something he was not sure he wanted to hear. The two nitrogen atoms live in a potential well roughly 9.8 eV deep; thermal energy at room temperature is about 0.025 eV. By every classical account the molecule is rock-solid — the activation energy towers over thermal jostling by a factor approaching four hundred. Hund had no reason to doubt that verdict. The Schrödinger equation, only two years old, was about to overrule it.

What stopped him was that the wave function refused to die at the edge of the classically allowed region. It leaked into the forbidden zone, decaying as it went, and emerged on the far side with amplitude that was small but stubbornly nonzero. The barrier, Hund realized, was not a wall at all. It was a region of exponential suppression — and exponential suppression, no matter how savage, never quite reaches zero. In principle the molecule could come apart without ever borrowing the activation energy. For nitrogen the barrier happens to be wide enough and deep enough that the dissociation rate is utterly negligible, so nothing dramatic follows. But the principle had shifted under everyone's feet, and that was the real news.

Two years on, George Gamow turned the same piece of mathematics loose on a riddle that had defeated nuclear physicists for a decade. An alpha particle sits trapped inside a nucleus behind a Coulomb barrier some 30 MeV high. The alphas that actually come out carry a paltry 4 to 8 MeV. Classically they are imprisoned forever. Gamow showed they leak — and that the leakage rate is so exquisitely sensitive to the height of the barrier and the energy of the particle that a factor of two in energy swings the half-life by twenty-four orders of magnitude. Uranium-238 and polonium-212 differ in decay rate by a factor of $10^{21}$, and Gamow's tunneling formula bookkept the whole of it. A decade-old puzzle dissolved into a single exponential.

What licensed both of those calculations is the subject of this chapter: what becomes of the world once the walls are finite.

