## The Rectangular Barrier: Tunneling

So give it one. Let $V = V_0$ for $0 < x < L$ and $V = 0$ elsewhere — a barrier of finite width. A particle with $E < V_0$ comes in from the left. Classical verdict: total reflection. Quantum verdict: something altogether different.

Three regions:

- Region I ($x < 0$): $\psi_I = Ae^{ikx} + Be^{-ikx}$, $\hspace{2pt}$ $k = \sqrt{2mE}/\hbar$.
- Region II ($0 < x < L$): $\psi_{II} = Ce^{\kappa x} + De^{-\kappa x}$, $\hspace{2pt}$ $\kappa = \sqrt{2m(V_0-E)}/\hbar$.
- Region III ($x > L$): $\psi_{III} = Fe^{ikx}$ (no reflected wave; nothing on the right to reflect from).

Match $\psi$ and $\psi'$ at both interfaces. The algebra is honest work but no more — four continuity conditions, four unknowns — and what falls out is exact:

$$T_\text{exact} = \left[1 + \frac{V_0^2\sinh^2(\kappa L)}{4E(V_0 - E)}\right]^{-1}.$$

<!-- → [CHART: T(E) on log y-axis from 10⁻¹² to 1, showing T_exact (solid) and T_WKB (dashed) vs E/V₀ — both curves below barrier, resonance peaks above barrier, vertical line at E=V₀] -->

![T(E) on log y-axis from 10⁻¹² to 1, showing T_exact (solid) and T_WKB (dashed) vs E/V₀ — both curves below barrier, resonance peaks above…](../images/06-finite-wells-steps-and-barriers-fig-04.png)
*Figure 6.4 — T(E) on log y-axis from 10⁻¹² to 1, showing T_exact (solid) and T_WKB (dashed) vs E/V₀ — both curves below barrier, resonance peaks above…*

That one formula holds the whole story — the dependence on barrier height $V_0$, on barrier width $L$, on particle energy $E$, all of it, exact, with nothing thrown away. Let me draw out what it is telling us.

For a thick barrier ($\kappa L \gg 1$), $\sinh(\kappa L) \approx e^{\kappa L}/2$, and the exponential swamps the denominator:

$$T_\text{exact} \approx \frac{16E(V_0 - E)}{V_0^2}\,e^{-2\kappa L}.$$

The WKB approximation (developed in Chapter 11) returns $T_\text{WKB} = e^{-2\kappa L}$. The two differ by the factor $16E(V_0-E)/V_0^2$ — a gentle prefactor of order unity whenever $E$ sits well below $V_0$. WKB nails the exponential suppression exactly and misses only that prefactor. For most reckonings, the exponential is the entire game.

And what an exponential it is. $T \propto e^{-2\kappa L}$: double the barrier width and you square $e^{-2\kappa L}$, so the transmission collapses. The scanning tunneling microscope, invented by Binnig and Rohrer in the early 1980s, lives off exactly this. One extra ångström of gap between tip and surface multiplies the tunneling current by $e^{2\kappa} \approx 7$ to $10$, depending on the material. That single decade of swing per ångström is what buys atomic resolution — the instrument is nothing but a tunneling-current meter, and the current is an exponential ruler reading the gap.

<!-- → [FIGURE: schematic of STM geometry — tip hovering over surface, tunneling gap d, wave function decaying exponentially in the gap, with annotation showing one-ångström change → factor-of-7 current change] -->

![schematic of STM geometry — tip hovering over surface, tunneling gap d, wave function decaying exponentially in the gap, with annotation…](../images/06-finite-wells-steps-and-barriers-fig-05.png)
*Figure 6.5 — schematic of STM geometry — tip hovering over surface, tunneling gap d, wave function decaying exponentially in the gap, with annotation…*

**Above the barrier** ($E > V_0$): now $\kappa$ turns imaginary. Set $k_2 = \sqrt{2m(E-V_0)}/\hbar$, so $\kappa = ik_2$ and $\sinh(i\theta) = i\sin\theta$. The formula becomes:

$$T_\text{exact} = \left[1 + \frac{V_0^2\sin^2(k_2 L)}{4E(E - V_0)}\right]^{-1}.$$

Now $T = 1$ exactly whenever $\sin(k_2 L) = 0$, that is, when $k_2 L = n\pi$. The barrier turns perfectly transparent when its width is precisely an integer number of half-wavelengths at the energy inside it. The wave fits the barrier; constructive interference makes the barrier vanish from the particle's point of view. These are **resonances**, and they are the quantum cousins of the anti-reflection coating in optics, or of a Fabry-Pérot cavity tuned to resonance. Step off resonance and $T < 1$ even with $E > V_0$ — the particle has energy to burn and still bounces partway back.

