## A Worked Calculation

An electron ($m_e = 9.109 \times 10^{-31}$ kg) with kinetic energy $E = 1$ eV strikes a rectangular barrier of height $V_0 = 5$ eV and width $L = 5$ Å. What is $T$?

First, $\kappa$:

$$\kappa = \frac{\sqrt{2m_e(V_0 - E)}}{\hbar} = \frac{\sqrt{2 \times 9.109\times10^{-31} \times 4 \times 1.602\times10^{-19}}}{1.055\times10^{-34}} \approx 1.025\times10^{10}\ \text{m}^{-1} = 1.025\ \text{Å}^{-1}.$$

Then $\kappa L = 1.025 \times 5 = 5.125$. Since $\kappa L \gg 1$, the thick-barrier limit governs.

$\sinh(5.125) = (e^{5.125} - e^{-5.125})/2 \approx (168.2 - 0.006)/2 \approx 84.1.$

Into the exact formula:

$$T_\text{exact} = \left[1 + \frac{25 \times (84.1)^2}{4 \times 1 \times 4}\right]^{-1} = \left[1 + 11052\right]^{-1} \approx 9.1\times10^{-5}.$$

WKB returns $T_\text{WKB} = e^{-10.25} \approx 3.5\times10^{-5}$.

The ratio: $T_\text{exact}/T_\text{WKB} \approx 2.56$. And the prefactor $16E(V_0-E)/V_0^2 = 16\times1\times4/25 = 2.56$. They agree to the digit, as they must. $\checkmark$

Now the physical sting in the tail. The transmission is $\sim 10^{-4}$ — small, but emphatically not zero. Widen the barrier to 10 Å and $\kappa L$ doubles to 10.25, so $T_\text{WKB}$ drops to $e^{-20.5} \approx 1.25\times10^{-9}$ — four more orders of magnitude gone. The exponential is merciless. This is why, in any tunneling calculation, the width of the barrier matters more than almost anything else.

