## Why There Is No Energy Debt

The popular telling of tunneling goes like this: "The particle borrows energy from the vacuum — the time-energy uncertainty principle allows it — crosses the barrier before the debt comes due, and repays it on the far side." The story is wrong, and it is worth being exact about how.

The uncertainty relation $\Delta E\,\Delta t \geq \hbar/2$ does not authorize a loan of energy for a stretch of time $\Delta t$. That is simply not what it says. Energy is conserved at every instant inside the barrier; the particle's total energy is $E$ in region I, inside the barrier, and in region III alike. The wave function within the barrier, $Ce^{\kappa x} + De^{-\kappa x}$, is a perfectly legitimate solution of the time-independent Schrödinger equation for a particle of energy $E$ in a region where $V = V_0 > E$. It is real and decaying rather than oscillatory — but it is the correct solution, full stop. No negative kinetic energy, no overdraft, no repayment schedule.

What actually happens is at once plainer and stranger than the borrowing fable: the wave equation demands nonzero amplitude in the classically forbidden region, and when the barrier is finite that amplitude survives to the far side and launches a transmitted wave. The transmitted amplitude is small because the decaying exponential has worn it down across the width $L$. That is the whole of it. The particle borrows nothing. It crosses because the mathematics of partial differential equations has never heard the phrase "classically forbidden."

