## Still Puzzling

**How long does tunneling take?** The formula for $T$ tells you the probability of crossing, not the time the particle spends inside the barrier. Several rival definitions of "tunneling time" populate the literature — the dwell time, the phase time, the Büttiker-Landauer time, the Larmor clock time — and they disagree with one another. Attosecond-streaking experiments (Eckle et al., 2008; Sainadh et al., 2019) have measured *something*, but what that something means theoretically is still under dispute. This chapter hands you $T$. It does not hand you a tunneling time. The framework simply runs out here.

**Does tunneling allow faster-than-light signaling?** The claim keeps resurfacing in popular accounts: a tunneled pulse can show a group velocity faster than $c$, so information must outrun light. What is really going on is pulse reshaping. The barrier preferentially passes and amplifies the leading edge of the incoming pulse — an edge that was already present before the barrier. The front of the pulse never moves faster than $c$; the barrier simply favors its early part. No information travels faster than $c$.

